      "type": "add",
      "id": "b01d4f5c740d8ef6",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "b01d4f5c740d8ef6",
        "text": "An ethno-territorial unit does not become a state as the collective actor of politics because it has certain natural characteristics or a specific organizational shape. Rather, the international system constitutes its actors and forces ethno-territorial units to take the form of an institutionalized state if they are to participate in international politics. As a minimal requirement of participation, the international political system demands an organizationally anchored capacity for collective communication.16 In a comparable way, the market constructs corporations as collectives; otherwise, they would indeed be nothing but bundles of individual contractual relationships.17 Something similar is true in law. Nomen ossibus inhaeret: Once the legal system has overcome the old prejudice and endowed \"mental substances\" with nomina by granting them the capacity to act and to have rights, it can access completely new conflict dynamics, with the help of which it can enormously increase its norm production. Inventing the enigmatic legal person was the great cultural contribution of law to the organizational revolution of the modern era, which immensely expanded attributions of action beyond the realm of natural personhood. The social substrate of the legal person, which has always been a subject of much controversy, can be adequately identified only when one acknowledges the bold notion that law ascribes legal personhood not only to individual human beings but also, under certain conditions, to mere streams of information."
      },
